[src:viper-config-go/environment-variable-p01] In this list, there is no environment variable that refers to the location of the user's *My Documents* directory, so there is no standard method for setting a program's home directory to be the *My Documents* directory.
[src:viper-config-go/environment-variable-p02] The command processors in DOS and Windows also support pseudo-environment variables.
[src:viper-config-go/environment-variable-p02] These are values that are fetched like environment variables, but are not truly stored in the environment but computed when requested.
[src:viper-config-go/environment-variable-p02] Besides true environment variables, which are statically stored in the environment until changed or deleted, a number of pseudo-environment variables exist for batch processing.
[src:viper-config-go/environment-variable-p02] In batchjobs, they can be retrieved just like environment variables, but are not actually stored in the environment.
[src:viper-config-go/environment-variable-p02] The returned values represent the status of the system in the moment these variables are queried; that is, reading them multiple times in a row may return different values even within the same command; querying them has no direct effect on the system.
[src:viper-config-go/environment-variable-p02] Since they are not stored in the environment, they are not listed by SET and do not exist for external programs to retrieve.
